[2] Virginia (Peninsula Health District)
Date: Tue 8 Jul 2014
Source: The Virginia Gazette [edited]
http://www.vagazette.com/news/va-vg-pertussis-reports-0709-20140708,0,6545519.story


Officials with Virginia's Peninsula Health District received no reports of pertussis, commonly known as whooping cough, during the 1st 4 months this year [2014], but received 5 reports of the illness in the last 2 months, a state health official said Tue 8 Jul 2014.

According to Dr. Nzinga Teule-Hekima, health director for the Virginia Department of Health's Peninsula Health District, those 5 cases are still under investigation and have not been categorized as confirmed. The Peninsula Health District includes James City, York, Poquoson, Williamsburg and Newport News. Hampton has its own health department. "These are provisional reports that have to go through all these different check marks to be confirmed," Teule-Hekima explained.

The VDH reported that Virginia saw 418 cases of pertussis reported in 2013, 55 of which were located in the Peninsula Health District. In 2012, 625 cases were reported in Virginia, including 30 in the Peninsula Health District. Nationally, according to the CDC, about 24 231 cases of pertussis were reported provisionally in the USA in 2013 and 48 277 in 2012.

While a case is being investigated, Teule-Hekima said the VDH district offices will circulate letters within their specific jurisdictions, through places like schools and churches, to let people know it may be present without identifying the specific source due to privacy concerns.

"Our whole point is to protect public health and make sure that people have the information they need," she said.

[Byline: Christine Sampson]

