[3] California (Riverside County)
Date: Wed 9 Jul 2014
Source: Desert Sun [edited]
http://www.desertsun.com/story/news/health/2014/07/09/whooping-cough-cases-riverside-county/12437001/â‚¬


One person has died, and nearly 10 times as many people have been diagnosed with whooping cough in Riverside County in 2014 compared to 2013. The number has spiked to 148 county residents infected with the contagious bacterial disease as of late June 2014. Five of those cases have been in the Coachella Valley. Only 15 Riverside County residents had been diagnosed with pertussis, or "whooping cough," at this time last year [2013], county health officials said.

"We need people in the general public to be aware it is circulating in their communities and to contact their health care provider if they're feeling sick and think it's pertussis or know they've had exposure to someone with pertussis," said Barbara Cole, director of disease control for the Riverside County Department of Public Health.

The numbers reflect a statewide epidemic putting infants, the elderly and others with compromised immune systems at risk. The state Pertussis Report for June 2014 shows there have been reported outbreaks at elementary, middle and high schools at counties throughout California, according to the California Department of Public Health. The number of cases throughout California is roughly 4558 in 2014, more than the 2532 that were reported in all of 2013. A total of 142 patients have been hospitalized, and 20 percent required intensive care.

