[4] Vermont (Windham County)
Date: Wed 9 Jul 2014
Source: My Champlain Valley [edited]
http://www.mychamplainvalley.com/story/d/story/windham-county-experiencing-rise-in-whooping-cough/11424/4ddXik-cjUOQs1KQrr0nrw


The Vermont Health Department says Windham County is experiencing a rise in whooping cough (pertussis) cases. There was a total of 11 confirmed cases of whooping cough during the month of June 2014. Ten of the cases were among children ages 3 to 17, and one was an adult. In July 2014, 5 more suspected cases were discovered. The Health Department says all but one of the confirmed and suspected cases are from Brattleboro.

"Anyone who has a persistent cough should be evaluated by his or her health care provider," said Susan Schoenfeld, deputy state epidemiologist for infectious disease. "People with suspected or confirmed pertussis should stay away from others until 5 days of antimicrobial therapy have been completed. We ask anyone with coughing illness to stay away from infants, and we recommend that pregnant women get vaccinated to pass some protection on to their newborn."

The Health Department says cases occurred as schools were closing or had closed for the summer.

[Byline: Joe Gullo]

